---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "A1C to eAG Calculator | Silicon Based",
  description: "Stop guessing your blood sugar levels. Convert A1C to eAG instantly with our precise calculator and understand the methodology behind the numbers.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the formula to calculate eAG from A1C?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The American Diabetes Association (ADA) uses the formula: eAG (mg/dL) = (28.7 * A1C) - 46.7. To convert this to mmol/L, you divide the mg/dL result by 18."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does eAG stand for?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "eAG stands for estimated Average Glucose. It is a way to report your A1C results in the same units (mg/dL or mmol/L) that you see on your daily blood glucose meter."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is it important to know my eAG?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Knowing your eAG helps translate the long-term A1C percentage into a more relatable daily average blood sugar number, making it easier to understand how your daily management affects your long-term health."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is considered a normal A1C level?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A normal A1C level is typically below 5.7%. Levels between 5.7% and 6.4% indicate prediabetes, and levels of 6.5% or higher on two separate tests indicate diabetes."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I convert eAG back to A1C?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, you can reverse the ADA formula: A1C = (eAG in mg/dL + 46.7) / 28.7."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "A1C to eAG Calculator",
      "description": "Convert your A1C percentage to estimated Average Glucose (eAG) in mg/dL and mmol/L instantly.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Silicon Based"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Silicon Based",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://siliconbased.dev/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "mainEntityOfPage": {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://siliconbased.dev/a1c-calculator"
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="siliconbased"
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/a1c-calculator"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>A1C to eAG Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Convert A1C to estimated Average Glucose (mg/dL & mmol/L)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="input-section">
          <label for="a1c-input">A1C Level (%)</label>
          <input type="number" id="a1c-input" value="7.0" step="0.1" min="4" max="20" placeholder="Enter A1C %">
          <p id="a1c-error" class="error-msg" style="display: none;">Please enter a valid A1C between 4% and 20%.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="results-section">
          <div class="result-card">
            <span class="result-label">Estimated Average Glucose (mg/dL)</span>
            <span class="result-value" id="eag-mgdl-result">154</span>
          </div>
          <div class="result-card secondary">
            <span class="result-label">Estimated Average Glucose (mmol/L)</span>
            <span class="result-value" id="eag-mmol-result">8.6</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding Your A1C and eAG</h2>
      <p>Managing your health requires understanding the numbers that define it. For individuals with diabetes or those monitoring their blood sugar, the Hemoglobin A1C test is a critical metric. However, A1C is presented as a percentage, which can feel abstract compared to the daily readings you see on a standard blood glucose meter. This is where <strong>estimated Average Glucose (eAG)</strong> becomes essential. Our A1C to eAG calculator bridges this gap, translating a long-term percentage into an actionable daily average.</p>

      <h3>What is an A1C Test?</h3>
      <p>The A1C test (also known as the HbA1c or glycated hemoglobin test) measures the average amount of glucose attached to hemoglobin in your red blood cells over the past two to three months. Because red blood cells typically live for about 120 days, this test provides a reliable, long-term snapshot of your blood sugar control. A normal A1C level is generally considered to be below 5.7%. Levels between 5.7% and 6.4% indicate a higher risk for developing diabetes (prediabetes), while an A1C of 6.5% or higher on two separate occasions indicates diabetes.</p>

      <h3>The Importance of eAG</h3>
      <p>While the A1C percentage is vital for medical professionals assessing long-term health risks, patients interact with blood sugar levels daily using different units: milligrams per deciliter (mg/dL) in the United States, or millimoles per liter (mmol/L) in many other parts of the world. The concept of <em>estimated Average Glucose (eAG)</em> was introduced to report A1C results in these familiar units. By understanding your eAG, you can better correlate your daily self-monitoring of blood glucose (SMBG) with your long-term A1C targets.</p>

      <h3>How is eAG Calculated?</h3>
      <p>The translation from A1C to eAG is based on rigorous scientific research, primarily the ADAG (A1C-Derived Average Glucose) study sponsored by the American Diabetes Association (ADA), the European Association for the Study of Diabetes (EASD), and the International Diabetes Federation (IDF). This study involved continuous glucose monitoring to establish a definitive mathematical relationship between A1C and average blood glucose levels.</p>

      <p>The calculator above utilizes the official ADAG formula to determine your estimated average glucose in mg/dL:</p>
      <div class="highlight-box" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color);">
        <code style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); background: transparent;">eAG (mg/dL) = (28.7 &times; A1C) - 46.7</code>
      </div>

      <p>To provide context globally, the calculator also converts this value into mmol/L. The conversion is straightforward—you simply divide the mg/dL result by 18:</p>
      <div class="highlight-box" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color);">
        <code style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); background: transparent;">eAG (mmol/L) = eAG (mg/dL) &divide; 18</code>
      </div>

      <h3>Example Calculation</h3>
      <p>Let's say your most recent lab results show an A1C of 7.0%. Using the formula:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>First, multiply the A1C by 28.7: <code>7.0 &times; 28.7 = 200.9</code></li>
        <li>Next, subtract 46.7: <code>200.9 - 46.7 = 154.2</code></li>
      </ul>
      <p>This means an A1C of 7.0% corresponds to an estimated average glucose of approximately <strong>154 mg/dL</strong>. To convert this to mmol/L, divide by 18, which gives you approximately <strong>8.6 mmol/L</strong>. This result helps contextualize your daily readings: if your meter frequently shows numbers well above 154 mg/dL, your next A1C is likely to be higher than 7.0%.</p>

      <h3>Limitations of eAG</h3>
      <p>It is important to understand that while eAG is a powerful tool, it represents an <em>average</em>. Two individuals with the exact same A1C and eAG could have vastly different daily blood sugar experiences. One might have highly stable blood sugars that hover constantly around their average, while the other might experience severe highs and deep lows that mathematically average out to the same number. For this reason, eAG should be used alongside—not as a replacement for—daily monitoring or continuous glucose monitoring (CGM), which provide insights into glycemic variability and time-in-range.</p>
      <p>Additionally, certain medical conditions can affect red blood cell turnover and thus alter the accuracy of the A1C test. Conditions like anemia, kidney failure, or certain hemoglobin variants (such as sickle cell trait) can cause A1C results to be falsely high or falsely low. Always consult with your healthcare provider to interpret your results within the context of your broader health profile.</p>

      <h3>Taking Action on Your Numbers</h3>
      <p>Knowledge is only as valuable as the actions it inspires. If your eAG indicates that your blood sugar is consistently running higher than your target range, there are several steps you can discuss with your healthcare team:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dietary Adjustments:</strong> Monitoring carbohydrate intake is crucial, as carbs have the most direct impact on blood sugar.</li>
        <li><strong>Physical Activity:</strong> Regular exercise can increase insulin sensitivity, meaning your body requires less insulin to process glucose.</li>
        <li><strong>Medication Review:</strong> Your doctor may need to adjust the timing, dosage, or type of medication you are taking.</li>
        <li><strong>Stress Management:</strong> Chronic stress can release hormones like cortisol that elevate blood sugar levels.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Whether you are newly diagnosed or a veteran in managing your health, converting your A1C to eAG provides a tangible benchmark for your daily efforts. Use this tool regularly to bridge the gap between your quarterly doctor visits and your day-to-day management.</p>

      <div class="related-tools">
        <p>Looking to calculate savings instead of health metrics? Check out our <a href="/discount-calculator">Discount Calculator</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the formula to calculate eAG from A1C?</summary>
        <p>The American Diabetes Association (ADA) uses the formula: <strong>eAG (mg/dL) = (28.7 &times; A1C) - 46.7</strong>. To convert this to mmol/L, you divide the mg/dL result by 18.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What does eAG stand for?</summary>
        <p>eAG stands for estimated Average Glucose. It is a way to report your A1C results in the same units (mg/dL or mmol/L) that you see on your daily blood glucose meter.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is it important to know my eAG?</summary>
        <p>Knowing your eAG helps translate the long-term A1C percentage into a more relatable daily average blood sugar number, making it easier to understand how your daily management affects your long-term health.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is considered a normal A1C level?</summary>
        <p>A normal A1C level is typically below 5.7%. Levels between 5.7% and 6.4% indicate prediabetes, and levels of 6.5% or higher on two separate tests indicate diabetes.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I convert eAG back to A1C?</summary>
        <p>Yes, you can reverse the ADA formula: <strong>A1C = (eAG in mg/dL + 46.7) / 28.7</strong>.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    const a1cInput = document.getElementById('a1c-input');
    const a1cError = document.getElementById('a1c-error');
    const eagMgdlResult = document.getElementById('eag-mgdl-result');
    const eagMmolResult = document.getElementById('eag-mmol-result');

    function calculate() {
      const a1c = parseFloat(a1cInput.value);

      if (isNaN(a1c) || a1c < 4 || a1c > 20) {
        a1cInput.classList.add('error');
        a1cError.style.display = 'block';
        eagMgdlResult.textContent = '--';
        eagMmolResult.textContent = '--';
        return;
      }

      a1cInput.classList.remove('error');
      a1cError.style.display = 'none';

      // ADA Formula: eAG(mg/dL) = 28.7 * A1C - 46.7
      const eagMgdl = (28.7 * a1c) - 46.7;
      // Convert mg/dL to mmol/L: divide by 18
      const eagMmol = eagMgdl / 18;

      eagMgdlResult.textContent = Math.round(eagMgdl);
      eagMmolResult.textContent = eagMmol.toFixed(1);
    }

    a1cInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);

    // Initial calculation
    calculate();
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .calc-grid { display: grid; gap: 2rem; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
    @media (max-width: 768px) { .calc-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

    .input-section label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); }
    input { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }
    input.error { border-color: #ef4444; }
    .error-msg { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; }

    .results-section { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .result-card.secondary { background: var(--bg-color); border-color: var(--border-color); }
    .result-label { display: block; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .result-card.secondary .result-value { color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 2rem; }

    .explainer { margin: 3rem 0; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer h2, .explainer h3 { color: var(--text-primary); margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.1rem; list-style: none; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; }
    .faq-section summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
    .faq-section summary::after { content: "+"; font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details[open] summary::after { content: "−"; }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }

    .related-tools { margin-top: 3rem; padding: 2rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; }
    .related-tools a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .related-tools a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
